411. Redire...denuo. Pleonastic expressions of this kind are common in the Dramatists. Cf. v, 767 redauspiewidmn danao, Ter. Hec. prol. ii. 30 (quoted on p. 116) refero denuo.

413. Lambinus appears to have had a collation of the Codex Turnebi (T), but it is doubtful whether he took the reading exemisti from this source. We have the phrase e vinclis eximere in vv. 204, 356, where Hegio is the subJeet; and it is quite possible that in some Renaissance copy the word eremisti was substituted here for emisisti on the strength of these passages. Here, where it is a slave who is spoken of as effecting the release of his master, emittere ea: vincli-s· may be a more suital ›le phrase. N iemeyer suggests that emisisti may be used with reference to emittat mana v. 408.

414. Ita.. The MSS. have ista (cf. Cas. 996 feci eqo istaec dicta quae uos dicitis), a form which appears to be not l'lautine (see note on v. 964). With id in this line, it cannot be said that ista is required by ea of v. 415. In Trin. 1170 ita has similarly become ista in the MSS.
